The example said to have been set by Pollio (C. ii. 1, Introduction), of reading his works to a circle of friends for their criticism and amusement before they were published, may have already begun to be imitated by other writers. The practice grew to be an intolerable nuisanoe in the course of time, as we gather, among others, from Persius (S. i. 15 sqq.), Juvenal (i. 1 sqq.; vii. 403 xiii. 32), Martial (ii. 27, &c.). Persons who had money and dabbled in literature in- flicted their productioris upon clients and others whom they bribed to listen and ap· plaud them. The author of the Dialogus de Oratore, attributed to Tacitus (c. 9), speaks with contempt of one Saleius Bas- sus, a poetaster, mentioned by Juvenal (vii. 80), who went about praying people to listen to his recitations, and hired and prepared a room for the purpose.
